{
  "doc_id": "25776",
  "text": "During development, mice express increasing levels of αsynuclein mRNA, peaking at postnatal day seven (P7) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The α-synuclein protein is mainly expressed in neurons and located in the presynaptic termini [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . So far, a number of animal models have been developed for the study of α-synuclein. Overexpression of wildtype or mutant α-synucleins in mice [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] or Drosophila [CITATION_7] resulted in pathological and behavioral phenotypes similar to those found in PD. Homozygous α-synuclein knockout mice are viable, fertile, and have apparently normal brain morphology. Hippocampal synaptic plasticity in these mice was identical to wildtype animals as judged by LTP measurements. However, an alteration of dopamine release in the nigrostriatal system was observed [CITATION_8] .",
